 1160 to 1179","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","TANKERSLEY, YORKSHIRE, ENGLAND":"Tankersley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Tankersley, Yorkshire, England":"Tankersley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Poitevin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Altered form of French <b>Poitevin</b>: habitational name for someone from Poitou, a former province in western France whose capital city was Poitiers. See also   Poitevent  , compare   Potvin   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Potvin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Lucien, Armand, Gilles, Alphonse, Andre, Cecile, Michel, Pierre, Adelard, Adrien, Aime, Benoit.","French Canadian: altered form of French <b>Poitevin</b> (see   Poitevint  ). Compare   Podvin   1 and   Potwin  .","In some cases possibly also French: variant (shortened form) of French <b>Poitevin</b> (see   Poitevint  , compare 1 above)."]},{"name":"Poitevent","meanings":["(2010: NA)","Altered form of French <b>Poitevin</b> (see   Poitevint  ).","History: This surname is listed along with its original form <i>Poitevin</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors. The Huguenot ancestor was Antoine Poitevin from France, who immigrated with his family to Charleston, SC, in 1685. His descendants also bear the surname <i>Poitevint</i>."]}]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘tendril’ or ‘creeper’, often used in metaphors describing the slender curvature of eyebrows, arms, hair, swords, lightning, and women's bodies."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady De Poitevin was born from about 1160 to 1179, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. She married Dolphyn De Tankersley before 1200, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Tankersley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"ABT 1160-1179–":"umbes 1160 kuni 1179–Surnud","1176–Male":"1176–Surnud","1158–Male":"1158–Surnud","1183–1258":"1183–1258","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1258":"1258","before 1200":"enne 1200","1158":"1158","ABT 1200":"umbes 1200","1200":"1200","1176":"1176","1183":"1183","1160":"1160","ABT 1160-1179":"umbes 1160 kuni 1179","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","TANKERSLEY, YORKSHIRE, ENGLAND":"Tankersley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Tankersley, Yorkshire, England":"Tankersley, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"ABT 1160-1179–":"vuodesta noin 1160 vuoteen 1179–Kuollut","1176–Male":"1176–Kuollut","1158–Male":"1158–Kuollut","1183–1258":"1183–1258","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","1258":"1258","before 1200":"ennen vuotta 1200","1158":"11